<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">FBA0005/13-14</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Baker </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Tilly</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">—Written evidence</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="subject"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Baker </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tilly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is pleased to respond to the call for evidence made on 13 January 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are heartened by the fact that the committee has chosen to look at the proposed changes to partnership taxation. In our view the process which led up to the publication of the draft Finance Bill clauses is an example of how in practice the well-thought out principles in the document “Policy making – a new approach” can all too easily become lost in the process of turning policy into legislation.  In our evidence we have chosen to concentrate on the decision-making process rather than on specific aspects of the draft legislation, because we believe that the committee will be interested in the broader issue of what lessons can be learned from what has happened here.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The policy imperative</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">new approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> makes it clear that the starting point for any tax changes should be an exposition of the policy imperative.  The original consultative document</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> did at least in part meet that objective.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It started with a clear statement of the policy underlying the original introduction of the tax legislation dealing with LLPs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“The original tax policy aim was to place members of LLPs in the same position for tax purposes as partners in a traditional partnership.”</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The consultation document then set out two areas of concern about the operation of the LLP rules in practice; both a consequence of the automatic presumption of self-employment of LLP members for tax purposes.  In HMRC’s view this presumption had resulted in unintended consequences which were inconsistent with the original policy aim.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These were:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 31.38pt; padding-left:4.07pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The use of LLP structures by businesses to avoid employment tax obligations for individuals who were in reality ordinary employees:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“There is evidence that the current rules are not producing the desired policy outcome across a range of sectors and income groups. At one end of the scale, groups of low paid workers who would normally be regarded as employees are being taken on as LLP members as a condition for their obtaining work. Unlike becoming a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">member of a traditional partnership, accession to membership of an LLP is not likely to be seen as a career aspiration or sign of status. This may instead have downsides such as the loss of certain benefits and protections associated with employment. In some cases, employees of a company are being transferred wholesale to the LLP as members.”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.78pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The use of LLP structures by the legal and financial sectors to enable high earning “employees” to benefit from the advantages of LLP membership:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“At the other end of the scale, individuals who would normally be regarded as employees in high-salaried professional areas such as the legal and financial services sectors are benefitting from self-employed status for tax purposes as a consequence of the arrangements in place, which then leads to a loss of employment taxes payable.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The overall objective was summed up in the Ministerial foreword</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Fundamentally, this consultation is about levelling the playing field. It will have no impact on those partnerships or LLP members that use partnership structures as Parliament originally intended.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The original consultation document thus set out a coherent view of why change was necessary:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it set out the policy objective;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it set out circumstances where that objective was not being met;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it proposed solutions; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> set out a test of whether or not the outcome would be successful.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There has been an extensive consultation process with a high level of engagement between HMRC and interested parties (the number of formal responses to the consultation document was unusually high) and the draft legislation is now in place.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Testing the outcome</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">So this is a suitable time to consider the draft legislation in the light of the policy objectives.  Does it meet the success criterion set out by the Minister?  As a reminder this was:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Fundamentally, this consultation is about levelling the playing field. It will have no impact on those partnerships or LLP members that use partnership structures as Parliament originally intended.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If we are to test the new legislation against that desired outcome we clearly need to know what Parliament originally intended.  There is no difficulty in this.  The LLP structure was originally introduced into the UK with the explicit intention of enabling established professional partnerships to continue to operate in the UK with at least </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some measure of protection against the risk of catastrophic claims which would bankrupt individual partners.  Without the ability to restructure as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> LLP there was a real risk that those partnerships would cease to operate or would re-domicile abroad.  The LLP regime was enacted to enable those businesses to remain and prosper in the UK.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Critically in this context those partnerships continued, at least as far as relationship between members was concerned, largely as they had done before conversion into an LLP.  So there was generally continuity in such matters as:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">partnership capital;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">drawings and profit shares;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">entry into, and retirement from, partnership; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> governance.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Fundamentally, the ways that professional partnership agreements were structured did not alter as a result of the change to LLP status.  That remains the case now.  Partnership agreements will have evolved, but the fundamental principles and approaches underlying partnership agreements have not changed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">So if the new legislation has achieved its intended outcome,  existing professional partnerships who are continuing to use a pre-LLP framework for their partnership agreement should be able to say “we are using a partnership structure as Parliament intended: this legislation will have no impact on us.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">This is manifestly not the case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">It is our experience, based on very extensive discussions with our own </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">clients, that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> the legislation will have an impact on virtually every professional partnership in the UK which operates as an LLP.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At the very least, each LLP will need to review in great detail its current partnership agreement to determine whether or not it will satisfy the new tests.  This is not a one-off requirement.  It will need to be done in respect of each individual member of the LLP every year and every time a new member joins or leaves the LLP.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">That in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">itself</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should give pause for thought.  But it is also likely that many partnerships will have to the make changes to the whole structure of their partnership agreements, particularly in the area of profit share entitlement, governance and capital structure.  Many partnerships will find that if they don’t do this they will be adversely affected by the new rules.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This brings us to the heart of the problem.  We are talking here about partnerships which are operating precisely as parliament intended when it brought in the original legislation establishing the LLP regime.  That legislation had no effect, and was not intended to affect, matters of partnership governance or profit sharing within partnerships.  Indeed it was very clearly intended to allow partnerships to continue to operate in the way that they had always done.  Yet the new tax regime will cause many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of those partnerships to make changes to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in which they operate, or face the real cost, and cash flow problems, of operating PAYE and NIC.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Clearly, if that is the outcome that the Government desired it has every right to introduce such changes.  But the consultation was framed precisely to ensure that partnerships operating as Parliament intended were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> affected.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Why has the policy objective not been achieved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What has gone wrong?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our view this has all come about because the wrong issue is being tackled.  Fundamentally the “unintended consequences”, though they manifest themselves as tax problems, are not created by the tax legislation – they stem from a flaw in the LLP legislation itself.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S4(4) of the Limited Liability Partnership Act 2000 states:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="para30"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“A member of an LLP shall not be regarded for any purpose as employed by the LLP unless, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">if he and the other members were partners in a partnership, he would be regarded for that purpose as employed by the partnership.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Those words clearly contemplated the possibility that in some contexts a person could be a member of an LLP but yet also be an employee.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proper construction of these words was discussed in the court of appeal in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Martin Tiffin v Lester Aldridge LLP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  They were seen, at the very least, to be problematic. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sir Nicholas Wall, who gave the leading judgement, concluded that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S4(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4) taken literally resulted in “absurdities”, because the hypothetical question which it raised could only ever be answered in one way.  As a matter of law if somebody was a partner in a partnership he could not also be an employee of that partnership, on the principle that one cannot be an employee of oneself.  In other words the apparent policy intent discussed at point 23 above turned out not to have flowed through into the legislation.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Court of Appeal resolved the issue in that particular case by adopting a purposive interpretation of the legislation.  But the fundamental problem of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S4(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4) was never addressed.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is of critical importance in this context, because the draughtsman of the income tax rules governing LLPs relied on the LLP 2000 Act definition.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  These rules are the basis on which HMRC currently treats all members of LLPs as self-employed and which have led to the unintended consequences addressed in the consultative document.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">So the problem which HMRC and the Government are trying to address in these new rules is actually rooted in a drafting flaw in the original legislation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When enacting the LLP Act Parliament appears to have intended that some members of an LLP could have employment status.  Unfortunately, because of the problems with the drafting, this was never properly enunciated.  The tax rules then built on this flawed drafting to create the current position under which all members of an LLP are treated as self-employed.  This then led to the “abuse” which HMRC now seeks to deal with through many pages of complex legislation.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What should have happened?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The answer to the dilemma was surely not to impose a whole new set of rules designed to tax certain individuals as if they were employees: the answer should have been to address the problems with the original legislation.   What should have happened, indeed we believe should still happen, is that there should have been a consultation across Government about clause 4(4) of the LLP Act in order to correct the defect and agree a set of rules to govern the circumstances in which a person who is a member of an LLP is treated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">for all purposes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as an employee.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC would certainly need to input into such a consultation, but this is not simply a tax problem.  There are significant employment law issues here as well (the appellant in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Tiffin </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">case was seeking to access employment rights even though he was an LLP member).  The whole issue needs looking at in the round.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If the proposals are enacted as they currently stand an individual may be in the position that under general law he/she is treated as self-employed – with none of the employment law protections available to employees – while at the same he/she is deemed to be employed for tax purposes.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This would be a highly unsatisfactory position.  We know from our own experience in bringing new partners into the firm that new entrants to the partnership have to weigh up their loss of employment rights against the advantages of being a member of the partnership.  Any current member of any LLP faces the very real possibility that they could end up effectively in “limbo” if these new rules are enacted as they currently stand.  Look one way and they are employees: look the other and they are self-employed.  Surely this can’t be allowed to happen.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What gone wrong in the consultation process to lead to this highly unsatisfactory outcome?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We should say immediately that we do not attribute the problems to any particular individuals either within Government, the HMRC or indeed the other parties to the consultation process.  But we do see what has happened here as symptomatic of what we believe is a problem with much tax policy making in the UK – that of looking at matters in a vacuum or through a very small lens.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is all too easy for consultations to move too quickly into points of detail.  Tax professionals, both within HMRC and in the private sector, are naturally interested in the minutiae of law and regulation, and once everybody gets stuck into the detail it becomes extremely difficult to stand back to look at the overall context.  So the debate becomes one of the finer points of, say, the definition of what constitutes capital or the date on which it is deemed to have been contributed, rather than one of whether there is any need for such a test in the first place.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is a similar danger of slicing matters into small discrete categories which are then dealt with without proper coordination.  If we just concentrate on partnership taxation there have been:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this consultation;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">changes to the loans to participator rules, which include partnership aspects;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the extension of the transfer pricing rules inter alia to include certain partnership matters;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the publication of draft legislation on 17 January on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">modernising the taxation of corporate debt and derivative contracts, which has an impact on partnerships with corporate members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> office of tax simplification review into partnership taxation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no evidence that all of these initiatives are being looked at in the round – they are all governed by separate agendas and timescales.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is a pressing need to ensure that whenever new tax policy initiatives are contemplated there should be an overarching review across Government to ensure that the detailed work is not done on tax policy until there is broad policy agreement across Government about the objectives and the desirability of change.  It is only at that point that detailed work should be done on potential tax changes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We would also add one further point.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Respondents answered the questions in the original consultation document with the reasonable expectation that the comments which they made would be seen in the context of the underlying policy objective.  We believe, for reasons set out in this letter, that the policy objective has changed significantly since the original consultation and that there is now a clear intention to bring LLPs which are operating in the way that Parliament intended within the scope of the policy. Had respondents known that there would be such an apparent shift in policy objective it is likely that responses to the consultation document would have been significantly different. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Partnerships are an important part of the UK economy and like any other business structure have continued to develop.  It is, we believe, generally acknowledged that there are some problem areas in partnership taxation and that the partnership tax code has to be supplemented by agreed HMRC practice.  So there is a place for an overarching review of the role of partnerships in the current environment.  But this is not a matter </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">simply for HMRC.  Indeed the tax aspects of any such review should only be considered once there is an agreement on the overall framework in which partnerships should operate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One of my partners summed up the situation very succinctly:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the disruption caused by these measures will greatly exceed the mischief they are intended to counter.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We would be happy to follow up any of these matters with the committee. Should you wish to discuss this response, please feel free to contact Andrew Hubbard on 0115 948 9695.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt">Our response concentrates on the disguised remuneration parts of the consultation rather than the hybrid LLP aspects of the new regime.  We have concerns about some</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt">of the rules relating to the latter and we will be taking these up directly with HMRC.  We do not propose to deal with them in this document.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt">Partnerships: a review of two aspects of the tax rules. 20 May 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">ITTOIA 2005, S863</span></p></body></html>